WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:12.840
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger, and today we're&nbsp;
going to talk about arithmetic with fractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:17.760
basically the operations of addition&nbsp;
and multiplication. So, in this series&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:22.240
on foundations of mathematics, we have so far&nbsp;
introduced the natural numbers starting from 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:30.040
2, 3, and so on, and now we've introduced&nbsp;
fractions. A fraction is an ordered pair (M,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:37.440
N) written M/N or M over N where M and N&nbsp;
are just natural numbers. We'll introduce&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:41.760
this notation for that statement: so MN&nbsp;
being natural numbers, we'll write it as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:50.560
"MN are natural numbers." This symbol stands for&nbsp;
"are" or "is." It's like a European Euro sign,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:54.600
resembling an element sign, except it extends&nbsp;
a little bit beyond to distinguish it from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:59.920
that. And "num" here does not represent&nbsp;
a set but rather a mathematical type.

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:04.560
In this foundational series, we are not going&nbsp;
to talk about infinite sets because infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:10.280
sets don't really exist, and we are going&nbsp;
to adopt the rather more historical point of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:15.640
view that something like the natural numbers&nbsp;
is a sequence that unfolds beyond our view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.640 --> 00:01:21.960
but that we have no right to claim that we can&nbsp;
grab all of them and put them all together in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.960 --> 00:01:28.200
a single collection or a single set. So this is&nbsp;
not a statement about set theory; it's a statement&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:35.200
about mathematical objects being of a certain&nbsp;
type. We'll say a lot more about that later on.

00:01:35.200 --> 00:01:40.440
I also remind you that fractions come with an&nbsp;
important notion of equality, that M/N is equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:50.960
to K/L precisely when M * L = N * K. Now, when we&nbsp;
establish a notion of equality like this, there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:59.840
an important logical step that we should make&nbsp;
sure about, and that is, suppose that M/N = K/L&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:10.920
and suppose that K/L also equals P/Q. Does it&nbsp;
then follow that M/N equals P/Q? We certainly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:17.920
want it to be true, and we must check that our&nbsp;
notion of equality has this transitive property.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:27.040
So let's do that. This first statement here is the&nbsp;
same as ML = NK, and the second statement is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:38.240
same as KQ = LP. If we take these two and multiply&nbsp;
them together, so we take ML multiplied by KQ,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:45.560
that's going to be equal to NK multiplied by&nbsp;
LP, which we've written here. Now we examine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:51.200
this and rearrange it using the associative&nbsp;
and commutative laws for multiplication. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:56.640
we take this M and Q and bring them together&nbsp;
and the L and the K together. Over here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.640 --> 00:03:02.600
we bring the N and the P together and the L and&nbsp;
the K together. Then we see that we have a certain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:12.080
multiple of LK equals another multiple of LK, and&nbsp;
so that multiple MQ has to equal that multiple NP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:19.480
and that's equivalent to what we wanted to show.&nbsp;
So we've used a basic fact that's worth pointing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:28.360
out. We've used this fact before on occasion: if&nbsp;
AB equals AC, then we can deduce that B equals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:36.960
C. So a multiple of A equals another multiple of&nbsp;
A means those two multiples have to be the same.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:41.760
Now that we have fractions, we have to define&nbsp;
what we mean by the sum of two fractions and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.760 --> 00:03:48.040
the product of two fractions. To define those&nbsp;
things, we're going to go back to our laws&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:57.480
for the division of natural numbers. I remind&nbsp;
you that A/B + C/D can be rewritten using the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.480 --> 00:04:09.840
laws for division that we've established. We&nbsp;
rewrite AB as A * D / B * D, and we rewrite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.840 --> 00:04:20.680
C/D as B * C / B * D. The reason why we do that&nbsp;
is that now the denominators here are equal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:25.760
and when the denominators are equal, we can add&nbsp;
the two divisions by just adding the numerators:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:42.000
so AD + BC / BD. That was a law for divisions of&nbsp;
natural numbers. For multiplication, A/B * C/D =&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:50.680
A * C / B * D. That was another law for divisions&nbsp;
of natural numbers. So we're going to use those&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:58.560
two to define the corresponding operations for&nbsp;
fractions. We're going to say that A/B + C/D&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:08.040
equals, by definition, A * D + B * C over BD. So&nbsp;
exactly the same expression that occurred there.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.040 --> 00:05:19.440
We're going to say that A/B * C/D is AC over BD,&nbsp;
exactly the same expression that occurred there.

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:31.200
For example, 2/3 + 5/4 is 2 * 4 + 3 * 5,&nbsp;
all of that over 3 * 4, and that's 8 + 15,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:44.560
that's 23 over 12. While the product 2/3 * 5/4&nbsp;
is 2 * 5 over 3 * 4, 10 over 12. Now, although&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:52.240
this could be reduced or replaced with 5/6,&nbsp;
there's no need to; it's correct as it stands.

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:57.200
Now that we've defined the operations of addition&nbsp;
and multiplication, we must check that they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:04.960
are well-defined. That means we have to check&nbsp;
that our notion of equality behaves well with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:16.000
respect to addition and multiplication, or more&nbsp;
precisely, that if A/B = A'/B' and C/D = C'/D',&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:25.120
then we must check that the sum of these two&nbsp;
equals the sum of these two. In other words,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:33.880
that AD + BC over BD, which is the sum of&nbsp;
these two, equals A'D' + B'C' over B'D',&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:42.320
which is the sum of those two. We also have&nbsp;
to do the same thing for multiplication.

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:47.520
What does it mean for these two to be equal? It&nbsp;
means that this times this equals this times this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:53.560
and I've written that out. What does it mean for&nbsp;
these two to be equal? It means that those two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.560 --> 00:07:01.960
are equal. Our problem is to go from this&nbsp;
and this (those are the assumptions) to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:08.280
proving this one. This is a very important&nbsp;
logical step when dealing with fractions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.280 --> 00:07:13.080
and there's no avoiding it. I'm afraid&nbsp;
that many undergraduates and graduate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:16.840
students have gone through their entire&nbsp;
mathematical careers without having made&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.840 --> 00:07:22.240
this kind of check, so here's a&nbsp;
good point to remedy these gaps.

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:27.600
Alright, so the answer, of course, is yes. How&nbsp;
do we do it? We take these two initial starting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:34.760
points and manipulate them. So we take this one&nbsp;
here and multiply both sides by DD', the product&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:45.240
D * D'. So there's AB' * DD', and then that&nbsp;
equals B * A' * DD'. We do the same kind of thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:51.680
with this one here. We multiply this one on the&nbsp;
left by BB'. So we have that times CD', and that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:59.760
times DC'. Those we know from our assumptions.&nbsp;
Now what we're going to do is add this thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:04.280
the left side here, to the left side here, and&nbsp;
that's going to be equal to the right side here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:11.320
plus the right side here. So I'm just taking this&nbsp;
plus this, writing it there, and this plus this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:21.120
writing it there. Now we stare at this and&nbsp;
rewrite it a little bit. So A'DD' we rewrite as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:30.520
A * D * B'D'. We rearrange it similarly, rearrange&nbsp;
that and that one and that one. Once we've done it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:35.480
that way, we see there's a common factor B'D'&nbsp;
here, and the distributive law allows us to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.480 --> 00:08:44.440
rewrite the left-hand side as AD + BC all times&nbsp;
B'D'. This side here can be rewritten in the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.440 --> 00:08:52.040
way as BD times this quantity, and then that's&nbsp;
exactly what we wanted to show here. So we've gone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:56.560
from the assumptions to what we wanted to show.&nbsp;
Notice we haven't used subtraction yet, which we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.560 --> 00:09:05.320
haven't defined. I'll leave the multiplication&nbsp;
check of well-definedness to you as an exercise.

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:09.080
Now that we have the definitions&nbsp;
of addition and multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:16.720
we need to check that the laws of arithmetic&nbsp;
hold for these operations. It turns out that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.720 --> 00:09:21.200
the laws of arithmetic are exactly the same&nbsp;
ones as we've already established for natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:28.000
numbers. It's going to be an important task&nbsp;
to check that they're actually valid. We'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:41.880
do that next time. I hope you'll join me.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

